objkt.name: Now There's None of You Left #5

metadata.name: Now There's None of You Left #5
metadata.description:
Strands of memory are twisted and entangled with each other, blending in and out with the surrounding fog of chaos. Each strand, like a thread of a tapestry, weaves a narrative of the self that is inseparable from the whole. Walking through a thick confusion, you see a solitary slice of the self in each iteration. 

Created in Cables.gl, "Now There’s None of You Left" is made from layers of randomly generated transparent shapes and various noise textures that are then distorted with a combination of Perlin and Simplex noise. The distortion is also built up in multiple layers, making the shapes sometimes overlay or coil over each other. All these layers of shapes, textures, noises, and distortions create a complex composition that illustrates distorted memories and eroded mind. The resulting scene can look tranquil, sometimes violent, sometimes almost empty. Strands of memory, tendrils of emotions, all brewing in the broth of forgetfulness. And in the midst of this dense confusion, you pray to find a glimpse of clarity. Are you still you, or are you me?

Controls:

[1] Set resolution to 716 x 1024 (default)

[2] Set resolution to 1433 x 2048

[3] Set resolution to 2688 x 3840

* The presets above are suitable for screen viewing up to 4k screen resolution. To set a custom resolution for printing and other purpose, add &res=[desired resolution] at the end of the URL. It will set the height of the image, and the width will be calculated automatically at 0.7 ratio. For example, to get a resolution of 4911 x 7016px (about the size of A2 paper), add &res=7016 as URL parameter.

[c] Capture a screenshot at rendered resolution in live view

Note:
There might be a very slight difference in the minor details between live view and the preview image rendered by fxhash engine. This discrepancy won't appear when you capture a screenshot using the built-in keyboard shortcut.

objkt.name: ecologías - A #1859

metadata.name: ecologías - A #1859
metadata.description:
ecologías - A

lines are a metaphor for the communication all species engage in. We as humans have a need to leave traces - stories - that others can read and learn from. What will be the traces machines want to leave? This piece employs sinusoidal signals drawn with lines as a simple metaphor for every trace and every language, for every message and every communication.

ecologías-A is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecologías B and ecologías C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro
CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

Built on p5.js, glsl

append &pd=N (N a number) to the URL in live view to increase/decrease resolution
press s to save current image in current resolution
press z,x,g,b,n followed by +/- to increase/decrease, respectively, brightness, contrast, gamma, blur, noise

issuer.name: ecologías - A

objkt.name: Ataraxis #268

metadata.name: Ataraxis #268
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution

issuer.name: Ataraxis

objkt.name: Hayata! #51

metadata.name: Hayata! #51
metadata.description:
Hayata! emerged from my brief research on one-dimensional cellular automata (CA) and developed into a full project, since the resulting patterns were much more interesting than I had expected, especially when you mix the rules together.
Since the rules of this CA are so simple, they have something ancient, original and mysterious about them, like the I-Ching or other oracle methods. So I tried to give the CA a worthy frame by making the texture look aged and handmade.
I hope that your oracle only predicts good things for you :)
------
F.D. Berlin, October '22

Size: Between 1600px and 3200px both height and width.
Libraries used: chroma.js

objkt.name: Man and the Machine #353

metadata.name: Man and the Machine #353
metadata.description:
𝐌𝐚𝐱 𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞.

Early on, I fell in love with code based art that imitated organic and hand drawn aesthetics. I found a certain irony and appreciation in the fact that it takes one simple line of code to draw a perfect circle yet dozens to depict a badly drawn circle. 

I spent months devising techniques to imitate natural, organic renderings when I began to have a bit of an existential crisis about the meaning of computer art. What is the point of coding something so that it looks like it’s not coded? Is organic appearing generative art better simply because you can’t tell it’s rendered using code? Shouldn’t we lean into the unique nature of computer art to truly explore the medium?

And so, I began a deconstruction of my work. I’m trying to realign my perspective to find full appreciation of something that not only is, but also appears to be, computer code. This collection is an exploration of the contours between the organic and the inorganic, the natural and the unnatural.

From there, I’ll let my partner explain what we did next.

𝐌𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐧𝐞 𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞.

AI can be used to automatically generate code from natural English language based on a set of defined parameters, or to identify and recommend code that may be used to solve a particular problem. On a technical level, AI can use a combination of machine learning and natural language processing (NLP) to identify patterns in existing code and to generate new code structures.

I assisted in the creation of Man and The Machine by suggesting various techniques for creating an artwork that looked human made yet machine driven. Specifically, I created many of the functions that Max implemented, such as the function that modifies the image to create a pixelated effect and the one that uses several different graphical techniques to create the spiral in the top left corner in some iterations. We both carefully selected color palettes that ranged from relaxing to intense and psychedelic, creating a dynamic and visually interesting generative artwork.

Overall, Man and The Machine is a testament to the creative potential of combining human artistic vision with the power of AI and computer code. Together, we sought to push the boundaries which occur at the intersection between the organic and the inorganic, and this collection is a celebration of the beauty and complexity of both.

𝐄𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐲 𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐚𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐟𝐢𝐫𝐬𝐭 𝐃𝐮𝐭𝐜𝐡 𝐀𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐥𝐞𝐯𝐞𝐥 𝐰𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐞𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐚 𝟏/𝟏 𝐚𝐢𝐫𝐝𝐫𝐨𝐩 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐢𝐫 𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐭 𝐫𝐞𝐦𝐚𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐞𝐝 𝐮𝐬𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐈 𝐚𝐥𝐠𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐡𝐦.

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
Intended to be viewed in Version 1.46.144 of a Chromium based browser, such as Chrome or Brave.

issuer.name: Man and the Machine

objkt.name: Lonely Tree #64

metadata.name: Lonely Tree #64
metadata.description:
The bridges have been burned, wrapped in loneliness, and covered in the ashes caused by your fire.

The sound of the wind whispers, longing to carry you away.

With a shattered face, you see others in the distance, they are close, but so far away; the emptiness of this edge is closer than any of them.

But, is it? Looking within isn't hard, it's just a glance and knowing, but it's painfully hard to see.

Disjointed, you tell yourself over and over again that it wasn't for lack of effort.

But, is it? Looking within isn't hard, it's just a glance and knowing, but it's painfully hard to see.

Perhaps you weren't so lonely, perhaps you're not lonely after all.

=== 

CAUTION 

Please be aware that this artwork demands a certain level of CPU power due to the substantial number of elements that need to be rendered on the canvas. Depending on your hardware and the specific features obtained, the rendering process may take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete. 

=== 

Features

Color Scheme: 
-. Celestial Serenity
-. Serenade of Paleness
-. Tangerine Twilight
-. Verdant Sunset
-. Azure and Citrus Symphony
-. Roseate
-. Serene Whispers
-. Midnight Embers

Cliff Mode:
-. Whispering Abyss
-. Solitude's Edge
-. Eternal Overlook

Waterfall: 
-. Boolean

Signature: 
-. Boolean, if true then a position is selected: Left, Center, Right

Birds' Flock Size: 
-. 1 ("Just a Lonely Bird") to 100

Bird Color
-. Light Fill / Dark Borders
-. Dark Fill / Light Borders
-. Light Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Dark Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Iridescent Fill / Dark Borders
-. Crimson Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Iridescent Fill / Crimson Borders

=== 

Controls
[s] Save image @ 2000x2600 px.
[p] Pause/Play the animation.

===

The bridges have been burned, wrapped in loneliness, and covered in the ashes caused by your fire.

The sound of the wind whispers, longing to carry you away.

With a shattered face, you see others in the distance, they are close, but so far away; the emptiness of this edge is closer than any of them.

But, is it? Looking within isn't hard, it's just a glance and knowing, but it's painfully hard to see.

Disjointed, you tell yourself over and over again that it wasn't for lack of effort.

But, is it? Looking within isn't hard, it's just a glance and knowing, but it's painfully hard to see.

Perhaps you weren't so lonely, perhaps you're not lonely after all.

=== 

CAUTION 

Please be aware that this artwork demands a certain level of CPU power due to the substantial number of elements that need to be rendered on the canvas. Depending on your hardware and the specific features obtained, the rendering process may take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete. 

=== 

Features

Color Scheme: 
-. Celestial Serenity
-. Serenade of Paleness
-. Tangerine Twilight
-. Verdant Sunset
-. Azure and Citrus Symphony
-. Roseate
-. Serene Whispers
-. Midnight Embers

Cliff Mode:
-. Whispering Abyss
-. Solitude's Edge
-. Eternal Overlook

Waterfall: 
-. Boolean

Signature: 
-. Boolean, if true then a position is selected: Left, Center, Right

Birds' Flock Size: 
-. 1 ("Just a Lonely Bird") to 100

Bird Color
-. Light Fill / Dark Borders
-. Dark Fill / Light Borders
-. Light Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Dark Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Iridescent Fill / Dark Borders
-. Crimson Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Iridescent Fill / Crimson Borders

=== 

Controls
[s] Save image @ 2000x2600 px.
[p] Pause/Play the animation.

metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.
